{"title_page": "Craig Cormick", "text_new": "{{Use Australian English|date=October 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{external links|date=November 2012}}\n\n[[File:Craig Cormick Time Vandals.jpg|right|thumb|Craig Cormick with his book, ''Time Vandals'', in 2012.]]\n\n'''Craig Cormick''' in an Australian science communicator and author. He was born in [[Wollongong]] in 1961, and is known for his creative writing and social research into public attitudes towards new technologies. He has lived mainly in [[Canberra]], but has also in [[Iceland]] (1980\u201381) and [[Finland]] (1984\u201385). He has published 30 books of fiction and non-fiction, and numerous articles in refereed journals. He has been active in the Canberra writing community, teaching and editing, was Chair of the ACT Writers Centre from 2003 to 2008 and in 2006 was Writer in Residence at the [[University of Science]] in [[Penang, Malaysia]].\n\nCormick's creative writing has appeared in most of Australia's literary journals including ''[[Southerly (journal)|Southerly]]'', ''[[Westerly (Australian literary magazine)|Westerly]]'', ''[[Island magazine|Island]]'', ''[[Meanjin]],'' ''The Phoenix Review'', ''[[Overland (magazine)|Overland]]'', ''Scarp'', ''4W'', ''Redoubt'', ''Block'', as well as in overseas publications including ''Silverfish New Writing'' (Malaysia) and ''Foreign Literature No 6'' (China). He has previously been an editor of the radical arts magazine ''Blast'', and his writing awards include the ACT Book of the Year Award in 1999<ref>[http://www.library.act.gov.au/find/history/frequentlyaskedquestions/Events/literaryawards/book_of_the_year/book_of_the_year_1999 ACT Book of the Year Award 1999]</ref> a [[Queensland Premier's Literary Award]] in 2006, a [[Victorian Community History Awards|Victorian Community History Award]] in 2015,  the [https://web.archive.org/web/20160917182423/https://actwritersblog.com/2015/12/17/act-writing-and-publishing-award-winners/ ACT Writing and Publishing Award] in 2015 and the [http://www.taswriters.org/events/tasmanian-writers-prize-2016/ Tasmanian Writers' Prize] in 2016.\n\nAs a science communicator he has worked for the [[Commonwealth Scientific and Industrial Research Organisation|CSIRO]], [[Questacon]] and the [[Department of Industry, Innovation and Science]], and has represented the Australian Government at many international science forums including [[Apec]] and [[OECD]] conferences, presenting on issues relating to public concerns about new technologies. In 2013 he was awarded the [http://www.asc.asn.au/blog/2014/02/06/asc-unsung-hero-2013-winner-craig-cormick/ Unsung Hero of Science Communications] by the [http://www.asc.asn.au/ Australian Science Communicators].  Since 2019 he has been serving on the Advisory Board on Education and Outreach to the Nobel Prize Winning [http://www.opcw.org/ Organisation for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons].\n\n== Literary career ==\n\nCraig Cormick went on to study journalism and creative writing at the [[University of Canberra]] \u2013 both areas which he continues to work in \u2013 with stints at the [[Canberra School of Art]], the University of Iceland and [[Helsinki University]]. He returned to the University of Canberra to study languages, public relations and sociology, undertake a Masters in Communications and then completed a PhD in Creative Communications at [[Deakin University]] in 2007.\n\nHis first books were self-published or picked up by small presses until ''[http://aiatsis.gov.au/publications/products/unwritten-histories/paperback Unwritten Histories]'' was published by [[Aboriginal Studies Press]] in 1998. The book subsequently won the ACT Book of the Year Award and received praising reviews. His work has a strong sense of satire, across themes that include exploration, isolation, duality and [[Ned Kelly]] (who appears at least once in each of his eight short story collections). He has written and published, on average, one book a year since 1998, including collections of short fiction, novels and non-fiction.\n\nHe has published scholarly articles on public attitudes to new technologies in publications including: ''NanoEthics'', the ''International Journal of Biotechnology''<ref>[http://www.inderscience.com/info/inarticle.php?artid=3604 Inderscience (IJB): \"Perceptions of risk relating to biotechnology in Australia\" by Craig Cormick]</ref> ''Agricultural Science'', ''Historia Ciencias Saude''<ref>[http://www.scielo.br/scielo.php?script=sci_arttext&pid=S0104-59702006000500011&lng=en&nrm=iso Historias Ciencias Saude: \"Cloning Goes to the Movies\" by Craig Cormick]</ref> (Brazil) and ''[[Choices Magazine|Choices]]'' (USA). He also authored the Australian Government reports, ''Cloning Goes to the Movies'', and ''What you really need to know about what the public really thinks about GM foods''.\n\nIn 2008 he fulfilled \"a life's dream\"<ref>A Voyage Around Mawson, The Canberra Times, 18 June 2010.</ref> and travelled to [[Antarctica]] as an Antarctic Arts Fellow, visiting the three Australian stations on the continent, [[Casey Station|Casey]], [[Davis Station|Davis]] and [[Mawson Station|Mawson]], publishing his experiences as ''[http://newhollandpublishers.com/au/travel/1255-9781742570082-9781742570082.html In Bed with Douglas Mawson: Travels around Antarctica]'', in 2011, which merges his two interests of science and creative writing.\n\nIn 2014 and 1015 he published the acclaimed ''[http://angryrobotbooks.com/books/the-shadow-master-by-craig-cormick/ the Shadow Master]'' series with ''[[Angry Robot Books|Angry Robot books]]'', in the US and UK, as was a guest author at the [http://www.convergence-con.org/ Convergence] fan convention in Minneapolis, and at WorldCon in Helsinki in 2018. In 2015 he also took part in [http://summer.yale.edu/ywc the Yale Writers Conference].\n\n== Writing awards ==\n{{refimprovesection|date=July 2019}}\n*  2019 Shortlisted for a [[Victorian Community History Awards|Victorian Community History Award]], for [https://www.ginninderrapress.com.au/store.php?product/page/1589/Craig+Cormick+%2F+Backseat+Drivers/ <I> Backseat Drivers</I>], 2018.\n*  2019 - Shortlisted for an [https://aurealisawards.org/ Aurealis Award] for Best Horror Book for [https://ifwgaustralia.com/title-the-years-of-the-wolf/ Years of the Wolf], 2018.\n*  2016 - Winner of the [http://www.taswriters.org/events/tasmanian-writers-prize-2016/ Tasmanian Writers' Prize] 2016.\n*  2015 \u2013 Winner of a [[Victorian Community History Awards|Victorian Community History Award]], for [http://www.publish.csiro.au/pid/7287.htm Ned Kelly under the Microscope], 2015.\n*  2015 \u2013 Winner of the [https://web.archive.org/web/20160917182423/https://actwritersblog.com/2015/12/17/act-writing-and-publishing-award-winners/ ACT Writing and Publishing Award] for ''[http://craigcormick.com/2014/05/26/uncle-adolf/ Uncle Adolf],'' 2015. \n*  2010 \u2013 Shortlisted for the [https://web.archive.org/web/20111002201656/http://www.actwriters.org.au/awards/writing-and-publishing-award.shtml ACT Writing and Publishing Awards] for ''[http://craigcormick.com/2009/01/11/futures-trading/ Futures Trading,]'' 2010.\n* 2006 \u2013 Winner of [http://Queensland_Premier%27s_Literary_Awards Queensland Premier\u2019s Award] for ''[http://craigcormick.com/2005/01/11/a-funny-thing-happened-at-27-000-feet/ A Funny Thing Happened at 27,000 Feet]'' ([[Steele Rudd Award]] for a collection of short fiction).\n* 2004 \u2013 Short-listed for a [[Queensland Premier's Literary Awards|Queensland Premier's Award]] for ''[http://craigcormick.com/2003/01/11/princess-of-cups/ the Princess of Cups]'' ([[Steele Rudd Award]] for a collection of short fiction).\n* 2000 \u2013 Second Prize in the Age Short Story Contest.\n* 2000 \u2013 Second Prize in the University of Canberra Short Story contest.\n* 2000 \u2013 Nominated for ACT Artist of the Year.\n* 1999 \u2013 [[ACT Book of the Year Award]] for ''[http://aiatsis.gov.au/publications